<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900904-0035</DOCNO><DOCID>900904-0035.</DOCID><HL>   Hedged-Investment,   Founder Both Make   Bankruptcy Filings</HL><DATE>09/04/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13</SO><IN>BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)SECURITIES (SCR)</IN><LP>   ENGLEWOOD, Colo. -- Hedged-Investments Associates Inc. andits founder, James D. Donahue, filed for protection fromcreditors under the federal Bankruptcy Code late Thursday.   Hedged-Investments is managing general partner of HedgedSecurities Associates Inc., a limited partnership. On Aug.23, Mr. Donahue told 500 Hedged Securities investors, viavideotape, that he had lost more than $100 million of theirmoney through stock-option trading, primarily involvingshares of UAL Corp. Attorneys for the firm say HedgedSecurities has only about $2 million in assets remaining.</LP><TEXT>   Hedged-Investments filed under Chapter 11 of theBankruptcy Code, which gives businesses protection fromcreditors while they formulate a reorganization plan. Mr.Donahue filed under Chapter 13, which grants similarprotection to individuals. Aeroturbine Energy Corp., anotherHedged Investments subsidiary, also filed for Chapter 11protection.   The Hedged-Investment filing listed more than 1,000creditors but provided few details about the company's assetsand liabilities. Lawyers for the firm said such informationwould be provided in future filings.   In a federal lawsuit filed last week, Weyerhaeuser Co.said its pension fund lost an estimated $35 million byinvesting in Hedged Securities. In separate suits filed instate district court here, Paradigm Partners Inc., Chicagosaid a pension fund it controls lost more than $15 millionthrough similar investments. Union Texas Petroleum HoldingsInc., Houston, said its pension fund lost about $8 million.</TEXT></DOC>